{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563682"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:02:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:02:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16847"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16847"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.1,0.15,0.07,0.67]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9537"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108982"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9537"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16847"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91352"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"592"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4101"},{"type":"tags","id":"4828"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9212"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22534"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32564"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108982"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 15-year-old girl presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset right-sided lower abdominal pain that began four hours ago. The pain is severe, constant, and associated with nausea and vomiting. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her last menstrual period was two weeks ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is tender in the right lower quadrant with voluntary guarding. Transvaginal ultrasound reveals an enlarged right ovary with a 5 cm simple cyst and minimal blood flow on Doppler. Serum beta-human chorionic gonadotropin is negative.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt diagnostic laparoscopy, the right ovary appears enlarged and dusky blue in colour, with multiple twists of the pedicle noted.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate surgical management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ovarian biopsy and frozen section","Right oophorectomy","Ovarian detorsion alone","Right salpingo-oophorectomy","Ovarian detorsion with cystectomy and oophoropexy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a typical picture of ovarian torsion in an adolescent girl. The sudden onset of severe unilateral pain, associated nausea and vomiting, and ultrasound findings are characteristic. The dusky appearance of the ovary at laparoscopy often raises concern about tissue viability, but this should not dictate management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOvarian detorsion with cystectomy and oophoropexy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. Even when the ovary appears dark or dusky, preservation should be attempted as most ovaries will recover after detorsion. The underlying cyst should be removed to prevent recurrence, and oophoropexy (fixing the ovary) may reduce the risk of future torsion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight oophorectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is overly aggressive and should be reserved for cases where there is obvious necrosis or strong suspicion of malignancy. The appearance of the ovary during torsion is not a reliable indicator of tissue viability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight salpingo-oophorectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is even more aggressive than oophorectomy alone and is not indicated in this scenario. The fallopian tube often appears congested but will typically recover with the ovary after detorsion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOvarian biopsy and frozen section\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary in this case as there are no concerning features for malignancy. This would delay definitive management and potentially compromise ovarian function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOvarian detorsion alone\u003C/strong\u003E, while better than removal of the ovary, may leave the patient at risk for recurrence if there is an underlying cyst that predisposed to the torsion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key principle in managing ovarian torsion, particularly in young patients, is to preserve ovarian tissue whenever possible. Multiple studies have shown that ovaries can recover even after prolonged periods of torsion, and the macroscopic appearance during surgery does not correlate well with final tissue viability.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ovarian detorsion with preservation of the ovary is the preferred management for ovarian torsion, even when the ovary appears dusky.","Most torsed ovaries will recover function after detorsion, regardless of their initial appearance.","Oophorectomy for ovarian torsion should be reserved for cases of obvious necrosis or malignancy."],"references":["Ashwal E, Krissi H, Hiersch L, Less S, Eitan R, Peled Y. Presentation, Diagnosis, and Treatment of Ovarian Torsion in Premenarchal Girls. J Pediatr Adolesc Gynecol. 2015 Dec;28(6):526-9. doi: 10.1016/j.jpag.2015.03.010. Epub 2015 Mar 28. PMID: 26168769. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26168769/","Jones T. Ovarian torsion: an overview. O\u0026G Magazine [Internet]. 2011 [cited 2024 Dec 4];13(1). Available from: https://www.ogmagazine.org.au/13/1-13/ovarian-torsion-an-overview/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91352"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16847"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91352"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-15T15:27:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-15T15:30:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9537"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108982"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{